        "id": "01982c8b-7cd3-7d09-b25b-245d39a6d897",
        "title": "“I am happy to join with you today in what will go down in history as the greatest demonstration for freedom in the history of our nation.”\n— Martin Luther King, Jr.",
        "description": "“I am happy to join with you today in what will go down in history as the greatest demonstration for freedom in the history of our nation.”\n— Martin Luther King, Jr. (1963)\nSource: \"I Have a Dream\" speech, March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom; *A Testament of Hope: The Essential Writings and Speeches of Martin Luther King, Jr.*, ed. James M. Washington (1986).\n\nPossible meanings\nIn his opening, King immediately frames the March on Washington as an event of monumental historical importance. By declaring it the \"greatest demonstration for freedom,\" he elevates the gathering from a mere protest to a pivotal moment in the nation's ongoing struggle to realize its founding ideals. This rhetoric legitimizes the movement's demands and unites the vast audience in a shared, historic purpose.\n\nDelivered at the Lincoln Memorial a century after the Emancipation Proclamation, this line also connects the Civil Rights Movement directly to Abraham Lincoln's legacy. King positions the march as the necessary continuation of the fight for true freedom that was left unfinished. It frames the struggle for racial and economic justice not as a radical break, but as the fulfillment of America's promise.",
        "preview": "“I am happy to join with you today in what will go down in history as the greatest demonstration for freedom in the history of our nation.”\n— Martin Luther King, Jr.",
