        "id": "01982c94-9ebe-7ed4-a0d1-57dc4170a3f6",
        "title": "“If I have seen further than others, it is by standing upon the shoulders of giants.”\n— Isaac Newton",
        "description": "“If I have seen further than others, it is by standing upon the shoulders of giants.”\n— Isaac Newton (1675)\nSource: Letter to Robert Hooke; published in *The Correspondence of Isaac Newton, Volume 1: 1661-1675*, edited by H.W. Turnbull (1959), Cambridge University Press, p. 416.\n\nPossible meanings\nOn its surface, this is a profound statement of humility, acknowledging that scientific progress is a cumulative enterprise. Newton is crediting his own remarkable discoveries to the foundational work laid by earlier thinkers such as Galileo, Kepler, and Descartes. The quote champions the idea that even the greatest genius builds upon the knowledge of past generations.\n\nGiven that the letter was addressed to his scientific rival Robert Hooke—a man of short stature with a spinal deformity—the phrase might also be a subtle, backhanded insult. In this interpretation, widely discussed by historians, Newton uses a veneer of humility to deliver a sharp personal jab. He simultaneously acknowledges his intellectual debts while possibly belittling his contemporary and competitor.",
        "preview": "“If I have seen further than others, it is by standing upon the shoulders of giants.”\n— Isaac Newton",
        "content": "“If I have seen further than others, it is by standing upon the shoulders of giants.”\n— Isaac Newton (1675)\nSource: Letter to Robert Hooke; published in *The Correspondence of Isaac Newton, Volume 1: 1661-1675*, edited by H.W. Turnbull (1959), Cambridge University Press, p. 416.\n\nPossible meanings\nOn its surface, this is a profound statement of humility, acknowledging that scientific progress is a cumulative enterprise. Newton is crediting his own remarkable discoveries to the foundational work laid by earlier thinkers such as Galileo, Kepler, and Descartes. The quote champions the idea that even the greatest genius builds upon the knowledge of past generations.\n\nGiven that the letter was addressed to his scientific rival Robert Hooke—a man of short stature with a spinal deformity—the phrase might also be a subtle, backhanded insult. In this interpretation, widely discussed by historians, Newton uses a veneer of humility to deliver a sharp personal jab. He simultaneously acknowledges his intellectual debts while possibly belittling his contemporary and competitor.",
