        "id": "01982ce0-acdb-7933-aa14-28724b4d15af",
        "title": "Friedrich Nietzsche",
        "description": "“In so far as the word \"knowledge\" has any sense at all, the world is knowable; but it is interpretable otherwise, it has no meaning behind it, but countless meanings.”\n— Friedrich Nietzsche",
        "preview": "“In so far as the word \"knowledge\" has any sense at all, the world is knowable; but it is interpretable otherwise, it has no meaning behind it, but countless meanings.”\n— Friedrich Nietzsche",
        "content": "“In so far as the word \"knowledge\" has any sense at all, the world is knowable; but it is interpretable otherwise, it has no meaning behind it, but countless meanings.— \"Perspectivism.\" It is our needs that interpret the world: our instincts and their \"for and against.\" Every instinct is a kind of thirst for power; each has its perspective that it would like to impose upon all other instincts as a norm.”\n— Friedrich Nietzsche (1901)\nSource: *The Will to Power*, Book Three, §560; trans. Anthony M. Ludovici, New York: The Macmillan Company.\n\n**Possible meanings**\nNietzsche introduces his concept of \"perspectivism,\" arguing against the existence of a single, objective truth. Instead, he claims the world has \"countless meanings\" because all knowledge is an interpretation shaped by the individual's unique biological and psychological needs, or \"instincts.\"\n\nThis process of interpretation is driven by the \"Will to Power\"—a fundamental drive in all living things to expand their influence. Each instinct creates a version of reality that serves its own quest for dominance, meaning our understanding of the world is not a passive reception of facts but an active imposition of our will.",
        "status": "published",
        "type": "article",
        "createdAt": "2025-07-21T12:06:18.584Z",
        "updatedAt": "2025-07-21T12:06:18.584Z",
