        "id": "01982ce1-3957-719d-8535-87f3fd5c5c56",
        "title": "Albert Camus",
        "description": "“Indeed, if I am in a desert, it is not because I love sand, but because I find nothing else. If I am not a Christian, it is not a sly way of saying that I am, but a naked and, if I may say so, a burning admission. There is no longer any question of a God, or of paradise, but of a world where one draws the consequences from certain facts and forces others to follow these facts. A world where one forces men to look at the world and at themselves without anything to give them hope but their own strength.”\n— Albert Camus",
        "preview": "“Indeed, if I am in a desert, it is not because I love sand, but because I find nothing else. If I am not a Christian, it is not a sly way of saying that I am, but a naked and, if I may say so, a burning admission. There is no longer any question of a God, or of paradise, but of a world where one draws the consequences from certain facts and forces others to follow these facts. A world where one forces men to look at the world and at themselves without anything to give them hope but their own strength.”\n— Albert Camus",
        "content": "“Indeed, if I am in a desert, it is not because I love sand, but because I find nothing else. If I am not a Christian, it is not a sly way of saying that I am, but a naked and, if I may say so, a burning admission. There is no longer any question of a God, or of paradise, but of a world where one draws the consequences from certain facts and forces others to follow these facts. A world where one forces men to look at the world and at themselves without anything to give them hope but their own strength.”\n— Albert Camus (1945)\nSource: \"The Cross,\" *Combat*, March 8, 1945; Reprinted in *Between Hell and Reason: Essays from the Resistance Newspaper Combat, 1944-1947* (2021), edited and translated by Alexandre de Vitry, Cambridge University Press, p. 119.\n\n**Possible meanings**\nThis passage outlines the core of Camus's absurdist and humanist ethics in the wake of World War II. The \"desert\" is a metaphor for a universe without God or inherent meaning, a reality he accepts not by choice but by observation. This honest confrontation with a meaningless world is the necessary first step toward creating human-centered values.\n\nIn this godless reality, morality and justice cannot be outsourced to a divine power or an afterlife. Instead, humans must take full responsibility for judging actions based on earthly facts and consequences, finding hope only in their own collective strength and reason. This was a direct argument for holding Nazi collaborators accountable, rejecting calls for Christian forgiveness in favor of human justice.",
        "status": "published",
        "type": "article",
