        "description": "Why collapsing stars create cosmic ripples\nhttps://temporary-cdn.ratio.global/generated-image-1753558576202-99k9z98k4vk.webp\nHow do spinning stars birth black holes and send out signals?",
        "preview": "Why collapsing stars create cosmic ripples\nhttps://temporary-cdn.ratio.global/generated-image-1753558576202-99k9z98k4vk.webp\nHow do spinning stars birth black holes and send out signals?",
        "content": "## Stellar Giants Collide Toward Black Hole Birth, Emit Waves\n\n**New models predict observable gravitational waves from supermassive star collapse.**\n\nSupermassive stars, colossal cosmic objects, likely spin up and distort on their way to becoming black holes, sending strong gravitational waves into space.\n\nAstronomers have long known that massive black holes reside at the cores of most galaxies, including our own. Yet, how these monstrous objects first formed remains a mystery. One leading idea suggests they sprang from the collapse of even larger \"supermassive stars\" or SMSs, ancient stellar giants weighing over a million times the Sun's mass.\n\nResearchers explored how these SMSs might evolve, focusing on their rotation and the gravitational waves [ripples in spacetime] they could produce. They wanted to know if these events might be detectable by instruments like the Laser Interferometer Space Antenna (LISA), a future space-based observatory.\n\nThe team modeled SMSs as if they were made of an ideal gas, tracking how they lose heat and shrink over billions of years. As these giant stars contract, they spin faster, much like a pirouetting ice dancer pulling in her arms. The scientists looked at two main scenarios: uniformly rotating SMSs, where the entire star spins like a solid block, and differentially rotating SMSs, where the core spins faster than the outer layers. The models used complex calculations based on Einstein's theory of general relativity.\n\nThe models showed that as a supermassive star contracts, it will eventually spin so fast that it could shed mass from its equator. A uniform spinner hits this \"mass-shedding limit\" when its internal rotation stress reaches about 9 one-thousandths of its gravitational binding energy. Even more dramatically, both types of spinning SMSs are very likely to deform into a peanut or bar shape, an event called a \"bar instability.\" This happens when the star's rotational energy reaches about 27 one-hundredths of its gravitational energy.\n\nOnce a supermassive star becomes bar-shaped, it radiates powerful gravitational waves that are \"quasiperiodic,\" meaning they pulse like a steady beat. For a 1 million solar mass star, these waves would have a frequency of about 10 millihertz, a range that LISA is designed to pick up. Such a bar-shaped star, located a billion parsecs [about 3.26 billion light-years] away, would produce gravitational waves with an amplitude, or strength, of about 4 x 10<sup>-15</sup>. Critically, these waves would persist for an incredibly long time, typically around 10,000 years, emitting billions of wave cycles. This long, steady signal could make them easier to detect.\n\n\"Our findings suggest that the bar instability is a highly probable outcome for collapsing supermassive stars,\" according to the study. \"This offers a distinct gravitational wave signature that future observatories could pinpoint.\"\n\nThe study notes that precisely predicting the gravitational wave signals requires more advanced 3D simulations. Future research must also better understand the initial conditions of these ancient stars and how viscosity [stickiness] and magnetic fields affect their spin.\n\nRegardless, the predicted gravitational waves from these forming black holes could open a new window onto the universe's most dramatic events.\n\nNew, K. C. B., & Shapiro, S. L. (2000). *The Formation of Supermassive Black Holes and the Evolution of Supermassive Stars*. arXiv. Retrieved from https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0009095",
        "status": "published",
        "type": "article",
