        "id": "019855a7-4a23-7188-ad16-6dfc3fcd9ea4",
        "title": "Some AI models solve complex cell growth math problems with 100 percent accuracy.",
        "description": "# AI Cracks Biology's Code\n\n<img src=\"https://temporary-cdn.ratio.global/generated-image-1753783675789-o8ul6a4r6na.webp\" alt=\"AI cracked biology's code\">\n\n> Can AI really outsmart scientists on cell growth?",
        "preview": "# AI Cracks Biology's Code\n\n<img src=\"https://temporary-cdn.ratio.global/generated-image-1753783675789-o8ul6a4r6na.webp\" alt=\"AI cracked biology's code\">\n\n> Can AI really outsmart scientists on cell growth?",
        "content": "# AI Masterminds Cell Growth Math\n\nA new study reveals that certain generative artificial intelligence (AI) models can *flawlessly solve* complex math problems related to how cells multiply.\n\nResearchers investigated what kind of math challenges generative AI models could handle, specifically in computational biology. Like a cosmic puzzle, they aimed to see if AI could grasp the intricate dance of cell division.\n\n---\n\n### Study Methodology\n\nScientists set up challenges for **six different AI models**, including OpenAI's ChatGPT and Anthropic's Claude 3.7 Sonnet. They presented the AIs with specific prompts and data, testing their ability to use a special mathematical model called **HCP (Infinite Series with Multiple Ratios)** to predict cell growth.\n\nThe AIs faced three stages of challenges, each one tougher than the last.\n\n### Key Findings\n\nSome AI models soared, while others failed:\n\n*   **DeepSeek R1, Grok 3, and Gemini Advanced 2.0 Flash:** Achieved perfect 100% accuracy in the first stage.\n*   **ChatGPT and Claude 3.7 Sonnet:** Could not solve the initial problems.\n*   **Grok 3:** Truly shined, demonstrating an ability to adapt and learn from its mistakes, reaching 100% accuracy in later, harder challenges.\n*   **Other AIs:** Did not improve, even with more information.\n\n> \"Grok 3 demonstrated exceptional problem-solving capabilities and adaptive learning abilities,\" state the authors.\n\nThese findings suggest some AIs are becoming increasingly sophisticated in handling complex scientific problems.\n\n### Significance and Future Outlook\n\nThis breakthrough matters because understanding cell proliferation is key in many fields, from medicine to agriculture. Imagine AI helping design **better cancer treatments** or **optimizing crop yields**—it's like having a supercomputer on your side in the microscopic world.\n\nThe study's scope was limited to a specific set of AI models and math problems. Future research will explore other AI models and even more complex biological challenges.\n\nThis research hints at a future where AI could become a *living tool* in scientific discovery.\n\n---\n\n**Reference:**\n\nFrança, C. R. (2025). *Mathematical Challenges for Generative AI in Computational Biology: Cell Proliferation and the Path to Living AI* (Version 1). Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15014381",
